00:01:48,154 --> 00:01:50,873
On December first, 2002 ...

3
00:01:50,874 --> 00:01:58,554
Dilawar, a young Afghan taxi driver, took three passengers for a ride.

4
00:02:01,434 --> 00:02:05,274
He never returned home.

5
00:02:10,994 --> 00:02:16,914
TAXI TO THE DARK SIDE

6
00:02:31,594 --> 00:02:37,181
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] When the sun started to go down, the sand started blowing.

7
00:02:37,181 --> 00:02:39,943
It was like a big dust bowl. And I'm thinking,

8
00:02:39,943 --> 00:02:42,713
"Boy, is it gonna be like this every night?"

9
00:02:42,714 --> 00:02:44,556
[PFC. Damien Corsetti, Mil-Intel, Bagram] I remember walking in to there for the first time:

10
00:02:44,556 --> 00:02:47,666
The smell...the smell is the first thing that hits you,

11
00:02:47,666 --> 00:02:52,462
And being from D.C., if you've ever been to the National Zoo

12
00:02:52,462 --> 00:02:58,553
When you walk into the elephant house there, that's the best way to describe it.

13
00:02:58,554 --> 00:03:02,393
There were a few of us that lived in the prison, and I was one of them.

14
00:03:02,394 --> 00:03:07,594
They built it up to be a big, scary place to the prisoners.

15
00:03:19,474 --> 00:03:24,193
After the invasion of Afghanistan, U.S. Forces occupied Bagram,

16
00:03:24,194 --> 00:03:29,273
An old Soviet airbase as a place to collect and interrogate thousands of detainees

17
00:03:29,274 --> 00:03:32,393
captured throughout Afgan and Pakistan.

18
00:03:32,394 --> 00:03:35,473
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] These were suspected Taliban.

19
00:03:35,474 --> 00:03:42,321
They were being caught by Special Forces throughout the countryside, brought to Bagram to be held,

20
00:03:42,321 --> 00:03:47,753
interrogated, determined if they were a high-value prisoner.

21
00:03:47,754 --> 00:03:51,593
[SGT. Anthony Morden, Mil-Pol, Bagram] These were not nice people at all.

22
00:03:51,594 --> 00:03:57,233
They were very evil people who, you know, definitely had violent intentions.

23
00:03:57,234 --> 00:03:59,833
On December 5, 2002 ...

24
00:03:59,834 --> 00:04:03,833
Dilawar, the taxi driver, was brought to Bagram.

25
00:04:03,834 --> 00:04:08,953
He was designed a PUC: Person Under Control, No. 421.

26
00:04:08,954 --> 00:04:13,513
[SGT. Anthony Morden, Mil-Pol, Bagram] He was something to do with a trigger man for a rocket attack.

27
00:04:13,514 --> 00:04:17,833
And that's about all I know.

28
00:04:17,834 --> 00:04:23,794
Five days after his arrival, he was dead.

29
00:04:28,754 --> 00:04:34,153
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] I would say this was around about 05:00 in the morning.

30
00:04:34,154 --> 00:04:38,268
As I walked by Dilawar...I think that's his name, Dilawar

31
00:04:38,268 --> 00:04:39,953
Walked by Dilawar's cell,

32
00:04:39,954 --> 00:04:43,753
I noticed that he was just kind of hanging there with his head down.

33
00:04:43,754 --> 00:04:49,633
But he was being too still to be, you know, just hanging there and sleep.

34
00:04:49,634 --> 00:04:53,633
[SGT. Anthony Morden, Mil-Pol, Bagram] SGT. Curtis opened up the door, and we went in.

35
00:04:53,634 --> 00:04:57,313
He was unresponsive. And we started CPR.

36
00:04:57,314 --> 00:04:59,753
[PFC. Willie Brand, Mil-Pol, Bagram] I was downstairs in general population.

37
00:04:59,754 --> 00:05:03,393
Then I heard a call come in asking for Cammack to come upstairs.

38
00:05:03,394 --> 00:05:07,599
He was a medic, and we carried him downstairs on a stretcher.

39
00:05:07,599 --> 00:05:12,460
And the Cammack was still on top of him while we're carrying him down, still trying to get him back going,

40
00:05:12,460 --> 00:05:17,645
all the way down the stairs. We got him through the front door and they kept working on him,

41
00:05:17,645 --> 00:05:21,394
kept working on him until the doctor got there and pronounced him dead.

42
00:05:21,394 --> 00:05:25,913
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] I don't know if it was an injury that was aggravated by something,

43
00:05:25,914 --> 00:05:29,193
or whether he was just sick coming in.

44
00:05:29,194 --> 00:05:31,593
[PFC. Damien Corsetti, Mil-Intel, Bagram & Abu Ghraib] They are very frail people,

45
00:05:31,594 --> 00:05:36,793
And I was surprised that it had taken that long for one of them to die in our custody.

46
00:05:36,794 --> 00:05:41,633
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] There was a definite sense of concern, because he was the second one.

47
00:05:41,634 --> 00:05:46,913
Just a week before Dilawar's death, another detainee at Bagram had died.

48
00:05:46,914 --> 00:05:49,489
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] You know, you wonder: Is this something we did?

49
00:05:49,489 --> 00:05:52,913
Or did somebody kill him or something? But I just didn't know.

50
00:05:52,914 --> 00:05:57,873
According to the medical examiner, the first detainee to die, Habibullah,

51
00:05:57,874 --> 00:06:00,553
had a preexisting pulmonary condition.

52
00:06:00,554 --> 00:06:05,633
But it was the beatings he sustained at Bagram that led to the cause of his death:

53
00:06:05,634 --> 00:06:08,873
A bloodclot that traveled to his lungs.

54
00:06:08,874 --> 00:06:10,985
[PFC. Damien Corsetti, Mil-Intel, Bagram & Abu Ghraib] When the second one died a week later,

55
00:06:10,985 --> 00:06:14,673
That's when it was like, "Oh, crap! Something's going to happen now."

56
00:06:14,674 --> 00:06:19,353
That's two prisoners dying within a week of each other. That's bad.

57
00:06:19,354 --> 00:06:26,273
A preliminary investigation into Dilawar's death, revealed deep bruises all over his body.

58
00:06:26,274 --> 00:06:30,393
But it did not conclude that his treatment at Bagram was to blame.

59
00:06:30,394 --> 00:06:35,156
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] The next day, they said, "Draw out how he was shackled up here."

60
00:06:35,156 --> 00:06:39,433
And I made that crude drawing.

61
00:06:39,434 --> 00:06:44,553
The ceiling of these isolation rooms was just a simple metal grate,

62
00:06:44,554 --> 00:06:49,793
And it was thick enough you could put handcuffs, you know, through the wires of that ...

63
00:06:49,794 --> 00:06:55,154
[Military Investigation Reenactment] And you just kind of chain them up like that, out to the sides, like this.

64
00:06:56,634 --> 00:07:03,473
Forced standing for long periods had inflamed tissue damage from blows to Dilawar's legs.

65
00:07:03,474 --> 00:07:08,593
But the initial Bagram press release failed to mention overhead shackling and beatings.

66
00:07:08,594 --> 00:07:14,034
It declared that both detainees had died of natural causes.

67
00:07:19,194 --> 00:07:24,791
[SGT. Anthony Morden, Mil-Pol, Bagram] My opinion is that the military wanted to get this over,

68
00:07:24,791 --> 00:07:30,394
and get this done quickly, before it really got noticed.

69
00:07:30,394 --> 00:07:35,393
Soon after Dilawar's death, the officer in charge of interrogation at Bagram,

70
00:07:35,394 --> 00:07:40,993
Captain Carolyn Wood, was awarded the bronze star for valor.

71
00:07:40,994 --> 00:07:45,113
Following the Iraq invasion, Wood and her intelligence unit,

72
00:07:45,114 --> 00:07:47,753
were given a new assignment:

73
00:07:47,754 --> 00:07:50,273
Abu Ghraib.

74
00:07:50,274 --> 00:07:56,154
A FEW BAD APPLES

75
00:08:03,234 --> 00:08:07,473
[Eric Lahammer, Mil-Intel, Bagram & Abu Ghraib] The only thing I can really remember about Abu Ghraib was the heat.

76
00:08:07,474 --> 00:08:12,393
It was like 148 degrees(58 ° C) or so there and it was all concrete.

77
00:08:12,394 --> 00:08:18,793
Abu Ghraib also had the infamous torture chambers and stuff left from Saddam's era.

78
00:08:18,794 --> 00:08:23,259
I remember walking through those and seeing like fingernail marks on the walls,

79
00:08:23,259 --> 00:08:27,149
And bloodstains, and guillotines and stuff like that.

80
00:08:27,149 --> 00:08:30,308
It was a pretty surreal feeling.

81
00:08:30,308 --> 00:08:38,264
We went to Abu Ghraib, I believe in July. July or August of 2003 to start that prison.

82
00:08:40,874 --> 00:08:45,714
[PFC. Damien Corsetti, Mil-Intel, Bagram & Abu Ghraib] You put people in crazy situations, and people do crazy things.

83
00:08:45,914 --> 00:08:48,233
And Abu was getting mortared every night.

84
00:08:48,234 --> 00:08:51,313
These 120 mm. mortars killing prisoners.

85
00:08:51,314 --> 00:08:56,153
The first time that happened, they should have evacuated those prisoners to somewhere else,

86
00:08:56,154 --> 00:08:59,433
Because the prisoners weren't safe.

87
00:08:59,434 --> 00:09:03,433
[SGT. Ken Davis, 372nd MP Company, Abu Ghraib] People were being told to rough up Iraqis that wouldn't cooperate.

88
00:09:03,434 --> 00:09:06,793
We were also told that they were nothing but dogs.

89
00:09:06,794 --> 00:09:11,153
Then, all of a sudden, you start looking at these people as less than human.

90
00:09:11,154 --> 00:09:14,073
And you start doing things to them you would never dream of.

91
00:09:14,074 --> 00:09:18,194
And that's where it got scary.

92
00:09:24,194 --> 00:09:27,193
[US Chief of Staff, Richard Myers] It was only the night shift. There's always a few bad apples.

93
00:09:27,194 --> 00:09:29,433
[Donald Rumsfeld, Secretary of Defense] It's been a body blow for all of us.

94
00:09:29,434 --> 00:09:32,273
[Lt. General Ricardo S. Sanchez] This is clearly an isolated incident.

95
00:09:32,274 --> 00:09:38,713
[General Geoffrey D. Miller] The conduct of a very, very small number of our leaders and soldiers.

96
00:09:38,714 --> 00:09:42,073
In the wake of media attention surrounding Abu Ghraib,

97
00:09:42,074 --> 00:09:44,873
the military began a series of investigations.

98
00:09:44,874 --> 00:09:48,753
[Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld, Abu Ghraib, 2004] The people who engaged in abuses will be brought to justice.

99
00:09:48,754 --> 00:09:52,793
The world will see how a free system, a democratic system,

100
00:09:52,794 --> 00:09:58,473
functions and operates transparently with no cover-ups.

101
00:09:58,474 --> 00:10:00,433
[Rear Admiral John Hutson, (ret) Judge Advocate General] The Secretary and others have said,

102
00:10:00,434 --> 00:10:02,833
"Well, you know, we've conducted 12 investigations"...

103
00:10:02,834 --> 00:10:07,473
Each and all of which were geared to looking downward,

104
00:10:07,474 --> 00:10:13,034
Down toward Lynndie England and Graner, and not looking up.

105
00:10:14,794 --> 00:10:23,593
The soldiers in the photos are military police, or MPs, whose job it was to guard and protect the prisoners.

106
00:10:23,594 --> 00:10:28,073
In their statements, the MPs claimed that Mil-Intel, or MI,

107
00:10:28,074 --> 00:10:34,273
Ordered them to weaken, humiliate, and break the prisoners for interrogation purposes.

108
00:10:34,274 --> 00:10:36,953
[SPC. Tony Lagouranis, Mil-Intel, Iraq] Obviously, you know, what they were doing, in those pictures,

109
00:10:36,954 --> 00:10:39,913
was not sanctioned by the Interrogation Rules of Engagement.

110
00:10:39,914 --> 00:10:44,433
And they weren't interrogators. So yes, I did think that they were bad apples.

111
00:10:44,434 --> 00:10:49,633
However, I also think that they were taking cues from Intel.

112
00:10:49,634 --> 00:10:52,313
[SGT. Ken Davis, 372nd MP Company, Abu Ghraib] This reading report said it was happening in Afgan.

113
00:10:52,314 --> 00:10:56,205
I mean, humiliation, trying to break people came from somewhere.

114
00:10:56,205 --> 00:11:01,073
MPs didn't think of it. MPs were not ever trained in such things.

115
00:11:01,074 --> 00:11:05,193
We should never have been "breaking" anybody.

116
00:11:05,194 --> 00:11:08,873
[PFC. Damien Corsetti, Mil-Intel, Bagram & Abu Ghraib] I can tell you, we set the same policies in Abu as we set at Bagram.

117
00:11:08,874 --> 00:11:12,313
The same exact rules.

118
00:11:12,314 --> 00:11:15,994
The same thing was going on.

119
00:11:16,754 --> 00:11:21,074
And they wonder why it happened.

120
00:11:22,594 --> 00:11:25,593
In her sworn testimony about Abu Ghraib,

121
00:11:25,594 --> 00:11:29,313
Capt. Wood said she felt pressured to produce intelligence,

122
00:11:29,314 --> 00:11:31,713
So she brought unauthorized techniques:

123
00:11:31,714 --> 00:11:38,593
Dogs, nudity, sleep deprivation and stress positions to Abu Ghraib from Afgan.

124
00:11:38,594 --> 00:11:43,393
Wood maintained that the Bagram model had tacit approval from superiors.

125
00:11:43,394 --> 00:11:48,873
But U.S. Central Command had never responded to her requests for authorization.

126
00:11:48,874 --> 00:11:54,153
So the mystery remained. Was Abu Ghraib the work of a few bad apples?

127
00:11:54,154 --> 00:12:00,593
Or evidence of a new world-wide system of detention and interrogation?

128
00:12:00,594 --> 00:12:03,553
[SPC. Tony Lagouranis, Mil-Intel, Iraq] I'm pretty sure that interrogators were telling the guards:

129
00:12:03,554 --> 00:12:07,583
"Strip this guy naked, chain him up to the bed in an uncomfortable position,

130
00:12:07,583 --> 00:12:11,753
You know, do whatever you can." And then they decided to take it one step further

131
00:12:11,754 --> 00:12:16,674
And have some "fun," and take pictures.

132
00:12:59,799 --> 00:13:02,274
[Colonel Lawrence Wilkerson, Chief of Staff to Colin Powell 2002-2005, 31 years in the Military]

133
00:13:02,274 --> 00:13:07,793
You've always got people in the military who are just this side of the Marquis De Sade,

134
00:13:07,794 --> 00:13:10,132
And one of the reasons you want rules

