00:19:33,954 --> 00:19:36,713
I mean that was a huge surprise for me.

212
00:19:36,714 --> 00:19:41,633
[John Galligan, Willie Brand's attorney] From a defense perspective, I immediately said "This is a political show trial."

213
00:19:41,634 --> 00:19:45,873
Willie Brand is a good soldier. Good soldiers tend to obey orders.

214
00:19:45,874 --> 00:19:50,633
Good soldiers tend to be people who do what they are trained to do.

215
00:19:50,634 --> 00:19:55,393
[Tim Golden, New York Times Reporter] The interrogators on the ground for the most part didn't know what the rules were.

216
00:19:55,394 --> 00:19:57,553
They'd never been interrogators before.

217
00:19:57,554 --> 00:20:02,382
[PFC. Damien Corsetti, 519th Mil-Intel Unit, Bagram, Afgan] My interrogation training consisted basically of,

218
00:20:02,382 --> 00:20:06,473
They taught us some approaches...you know...how to get people to talk.

219
00:20:06,474 --> 00:20:10,844
And then..."Here, go watch these guys interrogate"...

220
00:20:10,844 --> 00:20:12,913
which were the people that we were replacing...

221
00:20:12,914 --> 00:20:17,993
For about five or six hours before I did my first interrogation.

222
00:20:17,994 --> 00:20:20,593
[William Cassara, Damien Corsetti's attorney] Damien was picked for this job because he's big,

223
00:20:20,594 --> 00:20:25,273
He's loud, and he's scary. That was his qualification.

224
00:20:25,274 --> 00:20:28,393
[PFC. Damien Corsetti, 519th Mil-Intel Unit, Bagram, Afgan] "Soldiers are dying. Get the information."

225
00:20:28,394 --> 00:20:31,953
That's all you're told. "Get the information."

226
00:20:31,954 --> 00:20:36,197
[Tim Golden, New York Times Reporter] Soldiers said that when prisoners like Dilawar came into Bagram,

227
00:20:36,197 --> 00:20:38,953
They were immediately assaulted.

228
00:20:40,794 --> 00:20:45,953
They blasted music at them. Often, they had dogs barking at them.

229
00:20:45,954 --> 00:20:49,793
And they would use some of the most menacing

230
00:20:49,794 --> 00:20:53,713
Interrogators to create this sense of threat.

231
00:20:53,714 --> 00:20:56,433
One of those was Damien Corsetti.

232
00:20:56,434 --> 00:20:59,497
[PFC. Damien Corsetti, 519th Mil-Intel Unit, Bagram, Afgan] With the screening, you're trying to instill what's called "The Shock of Capture",

233
00:20:59,497 --> 00:21:03,722
When the person first comes in. And that's when they are most apt to give you information

234
00:21:03,722 --> 00:21:06,313
'cause they're just like, "Oh, crap, what's going on?"

235
00:21:06,314 --> 00:21:10,424
It's not just a disorientation procedure, it's actually a terrorizing procedure.

236
00:21:10,424 --> 00:21:14,073
It's designed to terrify you into spilling the beans, as it were.

237
00:21:14,074 --> 00:21:19,353
Being spat at. Being sworn at. Having the dogs barking around. Cameras flashing in your face.

238
00:21:19,354 --> 00:21:20,861
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] Keep in mind, in their culture,

239
00:21:20,861 --> 00:21:24,553
That dog's more shocking to them than it is to us.

240
00:21:24,554 --> 00:21:28,197
Kind of like a woman telling them what to do. You know, it's a cultural thing.

241
00:21:28,197 --> 00:21:31,073
So you get more bang for your buck, you know, with a dog.

242
00:21:31,074 --> 00:21:33,499
[Moazzam Begg, British subject detained at Bagram and Guantanamo 2002-2005] And then to be re-shackled, completely naked,

243
00:21:33,499 --> 00:21:36,953
and to do what they call "The Body Search,"

244
00:21:36,954 --> 00:21:43,914
The cavity search, and then to be questioned naked, shivering.

245
00:21:45,554 --> 00:21:47,633
[PFC. Willie Brand, Mil-Pol, Bagram] After they are read their rules and everything,

246
00:21:47,634 --> 00:21:51,753
They are taken to their cell, to where they're going to be put in sleep deprivation for 24 hours.

247
00:21:51,754 --> 00:21:53,953
That's standard for everybody.

248
00:21:53,954 --> 00:21:58,844
Then, from there, MI directs us that they can go to general population, or if they have to stay in isolation.

249
00:21:58,844 --> 00:22:02,378
And if they are going to stay in isolation, If they are going to be allowed to sleep.

250
00:22:02,378 --> 00:22:03,993
And if they can, then when.

251
00:22:03,994 --> 00:22:06,433
To weaken the defenses of detainees,

252
00:22:06,434 --> 00:22:11,473
Interrogators ordered Mil-Pol to find ways of keeping the prisoners awake.

253
00:22:11,474 --> 00:22:14,433
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] You know, they are in that room not saying anything...

254
00:22:14,434 --> 00:22:16,530
"Oh, well, maybe he knows a little bit more.

255
00:22:16,530 --> 00:22:19,713
Let's let him, you know, lose a little bit more sleep."

256
00:22:19,714 --> 00:22:24,286
Which is the idea of keeping them like this, so you won't sleep. You'll stand.

257
00:22:24,286 --> 00:22:29,621
Because as soon as you let your body go, that pressure on your wrist and your arms

258
00:22:29,621 --> 00:22:32,794
You're going to feel that with those cuffs on.

259
00:22:33,154 --> 00:22:38,500
[PFC. Damien Corsetti, 519th Mil-Intel Unit, Bagram, Afgan] The only time the MPs would ever help us do anything would be to keep them on a sleep schedule.

260
00:22:38,500 --> 00:22:40,899
You know, they are guaranteed so much sleep.

261
00:22:40,899 --> 00:22:44,071
Is that sleep consistent? Is it uninterrupted?

262
00:22:44,071 --> 00:22:46,553
You know, there's 15 minutes here, 15 minutes there.

263
00:22:46,554 --> 00:22:52,314
Who knows? That's how it was proposed to us.

264
00:22:52,474 --> 00:22:56,273
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] There would be a board, when you walked into the room, on his wall.

265
00:22:56,274 --> 00:22:59,993
You might see an arrow going up to the ceiling.

266
00:22:59,994 --> 00:23:04,793
And there would be maybe a "1" by it. So that would be an hour up.

267
00:23:04,794 --> 00:23:06,542
He's got to stand up for one hour.

268
00:23:06,542 --> 00:23:10,553
And then you may see a "2" with an arrow pointing down.

269
00:23:10,554 --> 00:23:13,393
That means he can sit down for two hours.

270
00:23:13,394 --> 00:23:16,593
[Tim Golden, New York Times Reporter] The prisoners were kept in these big pens downstairs.

271
00:23:16,594 --> 00:23:20,593
And their numbers would be scribbled on the door of the airlock,

272
00:23:20,594 --> 00:23:23,553
which was the little passageway that they were taken out of

273
00:23:23,554 --> 00:23:27,273
when they were brought up to the isolation cells upstairs.

274
00:23:27,274 --> 00:23:31,039
[Moazzam Begg, British subject detained at Bagram and Guantanamo 2002-2005] Detainees were actually chained, with their hands above their heads,

275
00:23:31,039 --> 00:23:36,142
in these airlocks. His number, "421," was something I could see often,

276
00:23:36,142 --> 00:23:37,576
because his back was towards me

277
00:23:37,576 --> 00:23:41,473
In the airlock, and the numbers were written on the backs of the detainees in black marker.

278
00:23:41,474 --> 00:23:44,913
And we all had that. As well as on the front.

279
00:23:44,914 --> 00:23:51,593
My number in Bagram was 180. But later it became "558."

280
00:23:51,594 --> 00:23:55,793
Thank you. It's good to be with you. It's good to be here in Bagram.

281
00:23:55,794 --> 00:24:00,753
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] I'm sure any high-ranking officer who toured would see the shackles,

282
00:24:00,754 --> 00:24:02,673
because they are going to tour to look.

283
00:24:02,674 --> 00:24:05,473
You know, they are curious just like everybody else is.

284
00:24:05,474 --> 00:24:09,505
[PFC. Damien Corsetti, 519th Mil-Intel Unit, Bagram, Afgan] There are always officers coming and going through the facility.

285
00:24:09,505 --> 00:24:13,296
We kind of joked about it as being The Greatest Show on Earth.

286
00:24:13,296 --> 00:24:16,473
Everyone wanted to come and look at the terrorists.

287
00:24:16,474 --> 00:24:20,993
Mr. Rumsfeld's office called our office frequently.

288
00:24:20,994 --> 00:24:27,673
Very high commanders would want to be kept up-to-date on a daily basis on certain prisoners there.

289
00:24:27,674 --> 00:24:30,917
The Brass knew. They saw them shackled. They saw them hooded.

290
00:24:30,917 --> 00:24:34,473
And they said, "Right on! You're doing a great job!"

291
00:24:34,474 --> 00:24:39,277
When the Red Cross toured Bagram, the sleep deprivation chart was erased.

292
00:24:39,277 --> 00:24:42,073
And the prisoners were unshackled.

293
00:24:42,074 --> 00:24:47,793
[Tim Golden, New York Times Reporter] Traditional military procedure did not allow you to shackle somebody to a fixed object.

294
00:24:47,794 --> 00:24:51,473
Certainly not chaining their arms overhead.

295
00:24:51,474 --> 00:24:58,113
Initially they were handcuffing people into the airlock of the cells for punishment.

296
00:24:58,114 --> 00:25:02,111
And that was to be strictly limited. 15 minutes. Half an hour.

297
00:25:02,111 --> 00:25:06,010
But it quickly "evolved". And when you walked in there,

298
00:25:06,010 --> 00:25:13,233
They just had a pair of long handcuffs dangling from the wire mesh ceiling of the cell.

299
00:25:13,234 --> 00:25:17,314
Ready for whoever came in.

300
00:25:25,104 --> 00:25:30,874
Manner of Death: Homicide

301
00:25:30,874 --> 00:25:36,713
The Army Coroner who examined Dilawar discovered massive tissue damage in his legs.

302
00:25:36,714 --> 00:25:41,639
She later testified that his legs had been pulpified.

303
00:25:41,639 --> 00:25:45,313
But what could have caused that kind of damage?

304
00:25:51,434 --> 00:25:55,753
In a videotape that surfaced as part of the homicide investigation,

305
00:25:55,754 --> 00:26:00,873
Colonel David Hayden, the top Army lawyer for U.S. Forces in Afgan,

306
00:26:00,874 --> 00:26:05,153
described a policy of shackling and striking detainees.

307
00:26:14,314 --> 00:26:17,113
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] I didn't actually hear a higher-up say,

308
00:26:17,114 --> 00:26:20,113
"Go and kick them in the leg if they do this and they do that."

309
00:26:20,114 --> 00:26:23,926
But the higher-ups said, "In order to get control of them,

310
00:26:23,926 --> 00:26:26,233
That's an option that you can use."

311
00:26:26,234 --> 00:26:31,378
[PFC. Willie Brand, Mil-Pol, Bagram] It's just your knee going into the side of their thigh about mid-way up.

312
00:26:31,378 --> 00:26:38,073
There's supposed to be a pressure point right there. And it controls them really easy.

313
00:26:43,434 --> 00:26:47,113
[Tim Golden, New York Times Reporter] Throughout the investigation, and even in the trials,

314
00:26:47,114 --> 00:26:55,009
a lot of the guards and interrogators described Dilawar as a very combative detainee, as a tough character.

315
00:26:55,009 --> 00:27:02,153
And that's just never been reconciled with all the other evidence that there was about this guy.

316
00:27:02,154 --> 00:27:05,673
He weighed 122 pounds when he died.

317
00:27:05,674 --> 00:27:09,713
The men who had been passengers in Dilawar's taxi told us later

318
00:27:09,714 --> 00:27:12,753
that he had just been absolutely terrified at Bagram.

319
00:27:12,754 --> 00:27:20,194
That they heard him through the walls of the isolation cells screaming for his mother and father.

320
00:27:21,114 --> 00:27:23,607
[Moazzam Begg, British subject detained at Bagram and Guantanamo 2002-2005] He'd been in a very uncomfortable position

321
00:27:23,607 --> 00:27:27,113
muttering some things, sometimes praying, sometimes asking for help,

322
00:27:27,114 --> 00:27:32,233
Or seemingly asking for help, because I couldn't understand his language.

323
00:27:32,234 --> 00:27:36,473
A number of witnesses remember the night before Dilawar died.

324
00:27:36,474 --> 00:27:40,713
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] Just that one night he got kicked in the leg, maybe like 10 times.

325
00:27:40,714 --> 00:27:44,591
[Tim Golden, New York Times Reporter] Some of the soldiers said they started using the knee strikes essentially to shut them up,

326
00:27:44,591 --> 00:27:47,000
Because he was yelling and screaming.

327
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:51,113
[SGT. Anthony Morden, Mil-Pol, Bagram] The damage that was done was done from multiple strikes.

328
00:27:51,114 --> 00:27:55,030
And a lot of that could have been avoided had you known the person

329
00:27:55,030 --> 00:27:59,474
before you had fought with them, and used that exact technique.

330
00:28:00,154 --> 00:28:03,633
[Moazzam Begg, British subject detained at Bagram and Guantanamo 2002-2005] When they eventually came to take him to an isolation cell,

331
00:28:03,634 --> 00:28:06,393
I believe his body had become almost limp.

332
00:28:06,394 --> 00:28:12,113
One of the reasons why they began punching him was that they felt he was putting it on.

333
00:28:12,114 --> 00:28:16,473
He was in the airlock standing there with a hood over his head.

334
00:28:16,474 --> 00:28:21,553
He had his hands tied above his head, and he was moaning.

335
00:28:21,554 --> 00:28:24,913
[SGT. Anthony Morden, Mil-Pol, Bagram] He started to fight right there in the airlock.

336
00:28:24,914 --> 00:28:28,193
And the airlock has a front gate and a back gate.

337
00:28:28,194 --> 00:28:30,977
but on both sides There is barbed wire. But both sides are concertina wire.

338
00:28:30,977 --> 00:28:34,873
Neither of us officers wanted to get into the concertina wire.

339
00:28:34,874 --> 00:28:40,433
So we pulled him out of the airlock and put him on the floor, and put him into restraints.

340
00:28:40,434 --> 00:28:43,393
What kind of force did you have to use to subdue him?

341
00:28:43,394 --> 00:28:46,713
[SGT. Anthony Morden, Mil-Pol, Bagram] Physical force. He was struck.

342
00:28:46,714 --> 00:28:49,519
[SPC. Glendale Walls, Interrogated Dilawar at Bagram] There were like four MPs on this guy.

343
00:28:49,519 --> 00:28:53,793
And one of the MPs just kept giving him kidney shots.

344
00:28:53,794 --> 00:28:57,633
The other two, they'd slam him to the ground.

345
00:28:57,634 --> 00:29:01,273
And then the fourth one like jumped on his back.

346
00:29:01,274 --> 00:29:04,393
He got a big gash on his nose.

347
00:29:04,394 --> 00:29:08,215
[Moazzam Begg, British subject detained at Bagram and Guantanamo 2002-2005] There was no reason to hit him. Remember, he was shackled.

348
00:29:08,215 --> 00:29:13,922
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] Even when control wasn't an issue, it became "Well, I'm just going to do this to get mine in."

349
00:29:13,922 --> 00:29:15,785
And that's probably why they got in trouble.

350
00:29:15,785 --> 00:29:23,594
Because you really couldn't justify kicking the guy that much if he was just chained up.

351
00:29:24,274 --> 00:29:29,207
Dilawar was taken to an isolation cell where the knee strikes continued.

352
00:29:29,859 --> 00:29:34,234
In her statement at trial, the Army Coroner said his lower limbs

353
00:29:34,234 --> 00:29:37,145
looked like they had been run over by a bus.

354
00:29:37,145 --> 00:29:41,898
Had he lived, it would have been necessary to amputate his legs.

355
00:29:41,898 --> 00:29:44,506
[PFC. Willie Brand, Mil-Pol, Bagram] Then it kind of raised the question of like,

356
00:29:44,506 --> 00:29:48,112
"This is what we did to him." It's not just like this is what I did to him,

357
00:29:48,112 --> 00:29:53,835
or this is what Cammie did to him, or Morden or anybody. Just, "This is what we've done."

358
00:29:55,820 --> 00:29:57,979
[Tim Golden, New York Times Reporter] It's almost hard to fathom now.

359
00:29:57,980 --> 00:30:03,740
You had soldiers like Willie Brand who seems like this very gentle, kind of soft-spoken guy,

360
00:30:03,740 --> 00:30:09,687
But who testified that he struck Dilawar so many times in the leg that his knee got tired,

361
00:30:09,687 --> 00:30:12,496
and he had to switch to the other one.

362
00:30:12,959 --> 00:30:21,446
[SGT. Anthony Morden, Mil-Pol, Bagram] Sometimes I feel that I should have gone with my own morality

363
00:30:21,446 --> 00:30:25,606
more than what was common.

364
00:30:26,766 --> 00:30:33,922
One MP testified that the strikes became an amusement inflicted on Dilawar just to hear him scream "Allah."

365
00:30:33,922 --> 00:30:37,509
[SGT. Thomas Curtis, Mil-Pol, Bagram] Some would say, "Well, hey, you should have stopped this. You should have stopped that

366
00:30:37,509 --> 00:30:41,138
When you saw he was injured, or saw he was being kicked on this...

367
00:30:41,138 --> 00:30:44,046
Why didn't you do something?" That would be a good question!

368
00:30:44,046 --> 00:30:46,317
And my answer would be, "Well, you know, it was us against them."

369
00:30:46,317 --> 00:30:52,032
I was over there. I didn't want to appear to be going against my fellow soldiers.

370
00:30:52,613 --> 00:30:57,747
Which...is that wrong? You could sit here and say that was dead wrong.

371
00:30:57,747 --> 00:30:59,983
Go over there and say that!

372
00:31:03,527 --> 00:31:06,647
No one ever investigated who set the rules at Bagram.

373
00:31:08,281 --> 00:31:12,580
Investigators never asked Capt. Wood what senior officers

374
00:31:12,580 --> 00:31:18,895
had given orders to treat detainees in ways that were forbidden according to the Army Field Manual.

375
00:31:19,125 --> 00:31:23,957
MP Capt. Beiring was the only officer prosecuted in the case.

376
00:31:23,957 --> 00:31:28,662
His dereliction of duty charge was dismissed when the judge determined

377
00:31:28,662 --> 00:31:32,556
That no one had made clear what Capt. Beiring's duty was.

378
00:31:33,272 --> 00:31:38,532
In spite of repeated requests for proper training, rules of engagement for his soldiers,

379
00:31:38,532 --> 00:31:40,708
His superiors gave him neither.

380
00:31:40,708 --> 00:31:43,800
[SPC. Glendale Walls, 519th Mil-Intel, Interrogated Dilawar at Bagram] We were all worried about not having that written guidelines.

381
00:31:43,800 --> 00:31:47,582
But they kept reassuring us that it was coming.

382
00:31:48,830 --> 00:31:51,662
[PFC. Damien Corsetti, Mil-Intel, Bagram] We knew exactly why we weren't getting clear guidance,

383
00:31:51,662 --> 00:31:54,589
just in case something like this happened.

384
00:31:54,590 --> 00:31:58,709
[SPC. Glendale Walls, 519th Mil-Intel, Interrogated Dilawar at Bagram] If I had to do it again, I'd probably say "No."

385
00:31:58,710 --> 00:32:02,443
I'm not doing anything until I see something in writing.

386
00:32:03,530 --> 00:32:08,158
Do you think that looking back, you think you were misled?

387
00:32:09,599 --> 00:32:13,466
[SPC. Glendale Walls, 519th Mil-Intel, Interrogated Dilawar at Bagram] I think we all were.

388
00:32:42,011 --> 00:32:48,371
A week after September 11th, Vice-President Dick Cheney appeared on Meet the Press

389
00:32:48,371 --> 00:32:54,828
to describe how interrogation policies were about to change.

390
00:32:54,828 --> 00:32:55,861
PAY BACK

391
00:32:55,861 --> 00:32:59,038
[Vice-President Dick Cheney] They have to work so that the Dark Side, if you will.

392
00:32:59,038 --> 00:33:02,451
We've got to spend time in the shadows in the Intelligence World.

393
00:33:02,451 --> 00:33:07,727
A lot of what needs to be done here will have to be done quietly, without any discussion,

394
00:33:07,727 --> 00:33:11,743
using sources and methods that are available to our Intelligence Agencies.

395
00:33:11,743 --> 00:33:15,828
If we're going to be successful! That's the world these folks operate in.

396
00:33:15,828 --> 00:33:23,145
And so it's going to be vital for us to use any means at our disposal basically to achieve our objective.

397
00:33:23,145 --> 00:33:27,352
[Scott Horton, Chair, Committee on International Law, NYC Bar Association] It's very clear that it starts in the office of Vice-President Cheney.

398
00:33:27,352 --> 00:33:33,651
He had a very strong view that we were not as aggressive

399
00:33:33,651 --> 00:33:38,837
in dealing with people in interrogations as we could or should be.

400
00:33:38,837 --> 00:33:42,823
"Taking the gloves off." Being rough with detainees.

401
00:33:42,823 --> 00:33:49,542
If Dick Cheney was the primary architect of a new policy, John Yoo was the chief draftsman.

402
00:33:49,543 --> 00:33:55,757
He wrote guiding opinions that argued for a flexible approach to treating suspected terrorists.

403
00:33:55,757 --> 00:33:59,942
[John Yoo, Dept. of Justice, Office of Legal Counsel 2001-2003] The United States used to treat terrorism as a criminal justice problem.

404
00:33:59,943 --> 00:34:04,553
The September 11th attacks showed that the struggle with Al Qaeda had moved into warfare.

405
00:34:04,553 --> 00:34:11,976
And I think when a foreign entity for political purposes, can kill 3,000 Americans, and cause billions of dollars of damage,

406
00:34:11,976 --> 00:34:15,839
And try to eliminate the leaders of the American government,

407
00:34:15,839 --> 00:34:19,961
That sounds like war to most people. It doesn't sound like crime.

408
00:34:19,961 --> 00:34:22,741
President Bush declared a war on terror.

409
00:34:22,741 --> 00:34:28,791
But he raised questions about whether suspected terrorists should be protected by the laws of war:

410
00:34:28,915 --> 00:34:31,125
The Geneva Conventions.

411
00:34:31,910 --> 00:34:37,849
Atrocities that shocked the conscience of the world gave rise to the modern Geneva Conventions.

412
00:34:37,849 --> 00:34:44,925
International treaties meant to provide fundamental protections for every human being captured in wartime.

413
00:34:46,437 --> 00:34:52,595
In effect for over 50 years, Geneva offered legal protections and prohibited interrogators

414
00:34:52,595 --> 00:34:58,433
from using torture, murder, or even humiliating and degrading treatment.

415
00:34:59,434 --> 00:35:07,315
After 9/11, John Yoo worked closely with Dick Cheney's office and Alberto Gonzales, counsel to the President.

