976
01:22:03,321 --> 01:22:10,262
[Jack Cloonan, FBI Special Agent 1977-2002] If this man, after 6-1/2 or 7 years of torture, says that it's not efficient,

977
01:22:10,262 --> 01:22:16,635
it's inhumane, and it breeds contempt for the United States,

978
01:22:16,635 --> 01:22:22,018
He can stand up and be a moral voice on this issue.

979
01:22:22,018 --> 01:22:25,054
[Senator John McCain] We sent them to fight for us in Afgan and Iraq.

980
01:22:25,054 --> 01:22:29,781
We placed extraordinary pressure on them to extract intelligence from detainees.

981
01:22:29,781 --> 01:22:34,006
But then we threw out the rules that our soldiers had trained on,

982
01:22:34,006 --> 01:22:39,328
and replaced them with a confusing and constantly changing array of standards.

983
01:22:39,328 --> 01:22:44,721
And when things went wrong, we blamed them. And we punished them.

984
01:22:45,351 --> 01:22:48,288
I believe we have to do better than that.

985
01:22:48,288 --> 01:22:54,759
I strongly urge you to do justice to your men and women in uniform.

986
01:22:54,759 --> 01:23:01,096
Give them clear standards of conduct that reflect the ideals they risk their lives for.

987
01:23:03,926 --> 01:23:10,236
On October 5, 2005, as increasing numbers of detainee abuse cases came to trial.

988
01:23:10,236 --> 01:23:14,078
Senator John McCain proposed the Detainee Treatment Act.

989
01:23:16,018 --> 01:23:22,065
The bill sought a total U.S. ban on torture. As well as cruel, inhuman and degrading treatment.

990
01:23:22,065 --> 01:23:28,576
And it sparked a national debate. One in which the Devil was in the details.

991
01:23:28,576 --> 01:23:33,102
[Senator John McCain] Is it still permissible to use a wet towel and dripping water

992
01:23:33,102 --> 01:23:36,438
to induce the misperception of suffocation?

993
01:23:36,438 --> 01:23:40,073
[Lt. General Randall M. Schmidt, Author of "Schmidt Report"] The use of the wet towel, dripping water to induce the misperception of suffocation

994
01:23:40,073 --> 01:23:46,684
was one of the techniques requested by the JTF in their laundry list given up.

995
01:23:46,684 --> 01:23:50,577
It was never approved. It has never been a technique approved.

996
01:23:51,187 --> 01:23:56,829
[Professor Alfred McCoy, author A Question of Torture] One of the techniques that made the transition from the regime of the physical to the psychological...

997
01:23:56,829 --> 01:24:01,895
in fact the only one...was waterboarding. Because in the medieval era, under the Inquisition,

998
01:24:01,895 --> 01:24:08,775
it was done because of its horrible, physical aspects. It was done to purge and punish the heretic.

999
01:24:08,775 --> 01:24:14,919
You force water down the throat of the victim. The victim thinks that he's drowning. It's horrible.

1000
01:24:14,919 --> 01:24:17,910
Your body tells you that you're dying.

1001
01:24:18,558 --> 01:24:23,422
Right after 9/11, the CIA got approval from the White House for waterboarding.

1002
01:24:24,070 --> 01:24:28,900
An early test case involved the interrogation of Ibn Sheikh al Libi,

1003
01:24:28,900 --> 01:24:32,701
a man suspected of being the Emir of an al Qaeda training camp.

1004
01:24:33,351 --> 01:24:37,044
Initially, the FBI was in charge of his interrogation.

1005
01:24:37,044 --> 01:24:42,583
But the Administration was impatient with the slow results of the FBI's law enforcement techniques.

1006
01:24:42,583 --> 01:24:45,972
So they turned al Libi over to the CIA.

1007
01:24:45,972 --> 01:24:49,742
[Jack Cloonan, FBI Special Agent 1977-2002] He is secured. He was either duct-taped or hooded.

1008
01:24:49,742 --> 01:24:52,390
And he was going to be put into a box...

1009
01:24:52,390 --> 01:24:58,887
a plywood box for his own protection [makes disbelief sound]...for transfer to the airport.

1010
01:24:58,887 --> 01:25:01,298
[Professor Alfred McCoy, author A Question of Torture] They throw him on an aircraft, and they rendered him

1011
01:25:01,298 --> 01:25:04,369
through extraordinary rendition, to Egypt.

1012
01:25:05,003 --> 01:25:12,517
They later subjected him to two weeks of brutal torture, involving all of these techniques, including waterboarding.

1013
01:25:13,367 --> 01:25:16,518
And they got information from al Libi stating

1014
01:25:16,518 --> 01:25:22,446
that Saddam Hussein's regime had trained al Qaeda in chemical and biological warfare.

1015
01:25:22,446 --> 01:25:28,247
[Scott Horton, Attorney] One of the things we know about torture is that someone who is tortured

1016
01:25:28,247 --> 01:25:35,406
will tell his interrogator what he thinks the interrogator wants to hear.

1017
01:25:35,406 --> 01:25:37,850
[Col. Lawrence Wilkerson, former Chief of Staff to Colin Powell] The moment al Libi was waterboarded,

1018
01:25:37,850 --> 01:25:43,411
he started blurting things out. Well, rather than questioning what he was saying,

1019
01:25:43,411 --> 01:25:47,348
and going into it in detail to see if what he was saying could be corroborated,

1020
01:25:47,348 --> 01:25:52,776
they immediately stopped and ran off to report what al Libi had said.

1021
01:25:52,776 --> 01:25:57,472
And ended the torture. And bang...it gets up to the highest decision-makers

1022
01:25:57,472 --> 01:26:02,353
And all of a sudden Colin Powell is told, "Hey, you don't have to worry about your doubts anymore,

1023
01:26:02,353 --> 01:26:07,765
because we've just gotten confirmation that there were contacts between al Qaeda and Baghdad.

1024
01:26:08,982 --> 01:26:18,701
In February, 2003, then Secretary of State Colin Powell went before the United Nations to make the case for the war in Iraq.

1025
01:26:18,701 --> 01:26:22,066
[Colin Powell, Secretary of State] I can trace the story of a senior terrorist operative

1026
01:26:22,066 --> 01:26:27,242
telling how Iraq provided training in these weapons to al Qaeda.

1027
01:26:27,242 --> 01:26:32,454
Fortunately, this operative is now detained, and he has told his story.

1028
01:26:32,994 --> 01:26:38,097
[Professor Alfred McCoy, author A Question of Torture] A year later, the CIA branded al Libi a fabricator,

1029
01:26:38,097 --> 01:26:42,286
and rescinded all of the intelligence reports with that information in it.

1030
01:26:42,286 --> 01:26:47,012
So, in other words, you will get information, but you'll get false information.

1031
01:26:47,012 --> 01:26:53,293
[Scott Horton, Attorney] I think Colin Powell said that was the most embarrassing day of his entire life.

1032
01:26:56,216 --> 01:27:02,564
[Rear Admiral John Hutson (ret) Judge Advocate General] All the experts say that torturing people is not the best way to get information.

1033
01:27:03,254 --> 01:27:11,812
Breaking down the barriers between you and them, gaining their confidence is the best way to get it.

1034
01:27:11,812 --> 01:27:15,476
It takes some experience. It takes some talent. It takes some patience.

1035
01:27:15,476 --> 01:27:19,558
And then they might actually tell you something that is worthwhile.

1036
01:27:19,558 --> 01:27:22,560
And then if you want to prosecute them and execute them, go ahead.

1037
01:27:22,560 --> 01:27:25,852
[Jack Cloonan, Counterterrorism Task Force] If you want to be able to build a rapport with somebody,

1038
01:27:25,852 --> 01:27:31,612
You are their salvation, because their life as they know it is over.

1039
01:27:32,184 --> 01:27:35,907
"Is there something I can do for your kids? You concerned about them?

1040
01:27:35,907 --> 01:27:39,262
Do you want them educated? I'll get them educated.

1041
01:27:40,802 --> 01:27:47,519
What do you want? Tell me what you want. Script for me your exit strategy."

1042
01:27:47,519 --> 01:27:53,391
"How do you extricate yourself from this terrible situation that, by the way, you put yourself in?"

1043
01:27:53,774 --> 01:27:58,150
"Now, you can't go back home, can you?

1044
01:27:58,150 --> 01:28:04,644
No. So let's make peace with that. Let me help you find the strategy to give you a life."

1045
01:28:05,251 --> 01:28:08,135
And that's the way it worked!

1046
01:28:08,135 --> 01:28:13,102
The amount of information that they were able to provide us, pre-9/11,

1047
01:28:13,102 --> 01:28:20,602
to me it was extremely valuable. Who else was going to tell us about how you joined al Qaeda?

1048
01:28:20,602 --> 01:28:24,740
What did buy-out mean? How did they communicate?

1049
01:28:24,740 --> 01:28:29,422
Did they use Emaar-set satellite phones. Did Bin Laden use a body double?

1050
01:28:29,422 --> 01:28:34,840
So when we got all that information, we were able to do certain operations.

1051
01:28:34,840 --> 01:28:39,555
Cumbersome though it may be, it still to me was the way to do it.

1052
01:28:39,555 --> 01:28:43,224
And we don't have to apologize to anybody.

1053
01:28:44,383 --> 01:28:47,484
We don't know what revenge is coming down the road.

1054
01:28:47,484 --> 01:28:54,204
And if I wanted to incite the faithful, I'd just take that one picture with the dog collar on,

1055
01:28:54,204 --> 01:28:57,290
and just point to that. And look at the young brothers and say,

1056
01:28:57,290 --> 01:28:59,869
"You're duty bound now to get revenge."

1057
01:29:04,354 --> 01:29:09,067
[Professor Alfred McCoy, author A Question of Torture] The advocates of torture generally focus on the hypothetical.

1058
01:29:09,067 --> 01:29:11,879
They have this ticking bomb scenario they talk about ...

1059
01:29:11,879 --> 01:29:15,562
[Clive Stafford Smith, lawyer for Guantanamo detainees] which is, imagine that there's a ticking time bomb in Times Square.

1060
01:29:15,562 --> 01:29:18,433
It's about to go off. We've got the guy in custody.

1061
01:29:18,433 --> 01:29:22,579
He says he wants a lawyer. Do we respect his right to a lawyer?

1062
01:29:22,579 --> 01:29:26,472
Or to save a million lives do we apply the electrodes to his testicles?

1063
01:29:32,338 --> 01:29:39,107
[Professor Alfred McCoy, author A Question of Torture] 24, week after week, has on-camera displays of brutal torture ...

1064
01:29:39,107 --> 01:29:41,228
[Kiefer Sutherland] Just tell me what your connection with the terrorists is?

1065
01:29:41,228 --> 01:29:48,107
designed to stop some terrorist with a ticking bomb from killing hundreds of thousands, if not millions, of Americans.

1066
01:29:48,107 --> 01:29:49,684
[Superior] You're talking about torturing this man?

1067
01:29:49,684 --> 01:29:53,362
[Kiefer Sutherland] I'm talking about doing what is necessary to stop this warhead from being used against us.

1068
01:29:53,362 --> 01:29:55,693
[Clive Stafford Smith, Lawyer for Guantanamo detainees, including Moazzam Begg] It's just nonsense, though! Because then you ask,

1069
01:29:55,693 --> 01:30:01,924
"Hey, name me one time in the last 500 years when we've had someone in custody with a ticking time bomb?"

1070
01:30:01,924 --> 01:30:07,479
[Jack Cloonan, Counterterrorism Task Force] The likelihood of that ever happening is so remote.

1071
01:30:07,969 --> 01:30:13,857
Even if you're in that situation, who is to say if you beat 'em up, that you're going to get that information?

1072
01:30:13,857 --> 01:30:17,769
If a guy is that committed, I think he'll die before he gives it up.

1073
01:30:17,769 --> 01:30:22,040
[Professor Alfred McCoy, author A Question of Torture] Right after the release of the Abu Ghraib photos in mid-2004,

1074
01:30:22,040 --> 01:30:27,717
35% of Americans polled believed that torture was acceptable under some circumstances.

1075
01:30:28,273 --> 01:30:31,211
Even after the Abu Ghraib photographs.

1076
01:30:31,211 --> 01:30:37,234
And I think that shows the way that this kind of popular culture has built a constituency for torture,

1077
01:30:37,234 --> 01:30:43,220
which allows the Bush White House to get away with the way it twists laws and treaties,

1078
01:30:43,220 --> 01:30:46,548
and doesn't spark popular outrage.

1079
01:30:46,548 --> 01:30:49,409
On a conservative radio show,

1080
01:30:49,409 --> 01:30:54,440
Vice-President Dick Cheney openly defended the practice of waterboarding.

1081
01:30:54,440 --> 01:30:58,037
[Scott Hennen, WDAY North Dakota] Would you agree, a dunk in water is a no-brainer if it can save lives?

1082
01:30:58,037 --> 01:31:02,201
[Dick Cheney, Vice President] Well, um, it's a no-brainer for me,

1083
01:31:02,201 --> 01:31:06,116
but for a while there I was criticized as being the Vice President for torture.

1084
01:31:06,832 --> 01:31:09,826
["President" George W. Bush] We do not condone torture!

1085
01:31:09,826 --> 01:31:13,404
[Scott Horton, Attorney] "We do not torture"! Footnote: "As we define torture.

1086
01:31:13,404 --> 01:31:16,827
Which means exactly what we wish it to mean, and nothing else."

1087
01:31:17,301 --> 01:31:25,999
In the elections of 2006, the Bush Administration openly campaigned for harsh techniques the rest of the world defined as torture.

1088
01:31:26,374 --> 01:31:30,020
Bush and Cheney played on the fears of voters and politicians.

1089
01:31:30,020 --> 01:31:37,436
If Congress didn't give them the power to do whatever was necessary, how could Americans be safe?

1090
01:31:37,436 --> 01:31:42,748
["President" George W. Bush] In addition to the terrorists held at Guantanamo, a small number of suspected terrorist leaders

1091
01:31:42,748 --> 01:31:49,150
and operatives captured during the war have been held and questioned outside the United States

1092
01:31:49,504 --> 01:31:54,088
in a separate program operated by the Central Intelligence Agency.

1093
01:31:54,888 --> 01:31:58,992
Some ask, "Why you are acknowledging this program now?"

1094
01:31:59,522 --> 01:32:05,316
Some believe our Military and Intelligence personnel involved in capturing and questioning terrorists

1095
01:32:05,316 --> 01:32:11,015
could now be at risk of prosecution under the War Crimes Act!

1096
01:32:11,015 --> 01:32:14,715
Simply for doing their jobs in a thorough and professional way!

1097
01:32:15,271 --> 01:32:17,550
This is unacceptable!

1098
01:32:17,550 --> 01:32:25,299
The President was forced to disclose his secret CIA program when the Supreme Court acted to limit his wartime powers.

1099
01:32:25,299 --> 01:32:28,217
In the historic Hamdan decision,

1100
01:32:28,217 --> 01:32:34,677
the Court ruled that interrogations and trials of terrorists would be governed by the Geneva Conventions.

1101
01:32:34,677 --> 01:32:41,974
["President" George W. Bush] This debate is occurring because of the Supreme Court's ruling that said we must conduct ourselves

1102
01:32:41,974 --> 01:32:45,496
under the Common Article III of the Geneva Convention.

1103
01:32:46,652 --> 01:32:52,290
And that Common Article III says that there will be no outrages upon human dignity.

1104
01:32:53,447 --> 01:32:58,427
It's a, it's a, it's a, like...it's very vague! What does that mean?

1105
01:33:02,965 --> 01:33:05,776
[Senator Carl Levin, Senate Armed Services Committee] Do you believe that the use of testimony

1106
01:33:05,776 --> 01:33:12,924
which is obtained through techniques such as waterboarding, stress positions, intimidating use of military dogs,

1107
01:33:12,924 --> 01:33:19,515
sleep deprivation, sensory deprivation, forced nudity would be consistent with Common Article III?

1108
01:33:19,515 --> 01:33:25,016
[Alberto Gonzales, Attorney General] Well, sir, I think that most importantly, I can't imagine that such testimony would be reliable.

1109
01:33:25,016 --> 01:33:32,524
[Senator John McCain] Mr. Attorney General, do you believe that statements obtained through illegal, inhumane treatment should be admissible?

1110
01:33:43,814 --> 01:33:57,241
[Alberto Gonzales, Attorney General] Senator, well, again...I'll say this: the concern I would have about such a prohibition is,

1111
01:33:57,241 --> 01:33:59,509
"What does it mean?" "How do you define it?"

1112
01:33:59,509 --> 01:34:04,287
And WHO would define it? The Bush Administration introduced a new law

1113
01:34:04,287 --> 01:34:07,792
that would elude the restrictions of the Supreme Court.

1114
01:34:07,792 --> 01:34:11,816
[Col. Lawrence Wilkerson, former Chief of Staff to Colin Powell] In a legal sense, I think they wanted to discard the Constitution.

1115
01:34:11,816 --> 01:34:15,100
And they wanted to write a new one. But you can't do that.

1116
01:34:15,100 --> 01:34:17,946
So what you do is you throw a new interpretation on the old one.

1117
01:34:17,946 --> 01:34:21,295
And the new interpretation is the Executive in wartime

1118
01:34:21,295 --> 01:34:26,728
And perhaps this war is going to last forever...is all powerful.

1119
01:34:27,526 --> 01:34:30,754
Congress gave the President most of what he wanted.

1120
01:34:30,754 --> 01:34:37,353
He would agree to abide by the Geneva Conventions so long as HE could define their meaning and application.

1121
01:34:38,708 --> 01:34:46,479
A few detainees at Guantanamo might be put on trial. But the rest would no longer have access to habeas corpus:

1122
01:34:46,479 --> 01:34:50,473
The fundamental legal right to challenge their detention.

1123
01:34:52,503 --> 01:34:57,236
Planning a run for President, even Senator McCain voted for the bill

1124
01:34:57,236 --> 01:35:02,417
soon after the Bush Administration threatened to discredit him with Conservative voters.

1125
01:35:02,417 --> 01:35:09,318
[The Cafferty File...Immunity from War Crimes?] Buried deep inside this legislation is a provision that will pardon President Bush

1126
01:35:09,318 --> 01:35:12,889
and all the members of his Administration of any possible crimes

1127
01:35:12,889 --> 01:35:19,738
connected to the torture and mistreatment of detainees dated all the way back to September 11, 2001.

1128
01:35:19,738 --> 01:35:25,079
At least President Nixon had Gerald Ford to do his dirty work. President Bush is trying to pardon himself.

1129
01:35:26,325 --> 01:35:31,135
The pardon did not extend to frontline soldiers.

1130
01:35:31,135 --> 01:35:36,777
[PFC. Willie Brand, Convicted: Assault, Maiming, Maltreatment] The trial was a very confusing time for me, because I've never been through a trial before.

1131
01:35:36,777 --> 01:35:42,277
I didn't know what was really going on. I kind of just understood that, you know,

1132
01:35:42,277 --> 01:35:45,533
I was facing a lot of time in jail. That's the only thing I really understood about the whole thing.

1133
01:35:48,540 --> 01:35:54,021
[SGT. Anthony Morden, Pled Guilty to: Assault, Dereliction of Duty] Well, I was sent to jail, to a Military Correctional facility.

1134
01:35:54,021 --> 01:36:01,921
I've lost my full-time job. I have a bad-conduct discharge

1135
01:36:01,921 --> 01:36:07,291
Wwhich has hindered me in getting a new job in the same field.

1136
01:36:07,291 --> 01:36:14,720
I...financially it's just devastated me.

1137
01:36:14,720 --> 01:36:20,587
I'm just glad it's over. That's it. Glad I can get on with my life.

1138
01:36:22,511 --> 01:36:29,631
I had to plead guilty to assault, and two counts of dereliction of duty.

1139
01:36:29,631 --> 01:36:35,340
In exchange, they would say that I could go to jail for no more than four months.

1140
01:36:36,036 --> 01:36:39,254
Rather than spend the money that was being spent for that trial,

1141
01:36:39,254 --> 01:36:43,792
I think it could have been better spent in working on Army doctrine to make sure that other people

1142
01:36:43,792 --> 01:36:53,586
go into battle properly equipped, properly led, and with a full understanding as to what their new roles and responsibilities are.

1143
01:36:55,413 --> 01:37:00,016
[William Cassara, Damien Corsetti's Attorney] When a detainee is abused, or a detainee claims abuse,

1144
01:37:00,016 --> 01:37:02,782
they want somebody to take the fall for it.

1145
01:37:02,782 --> 01:37:06,626
And it's not going to be the person with eagles or stars on their shoulder.

1146
01:37:07,206 --> 01:37:12,827
No officer was ever convicted in the Dilawar case.

1147
01:37:12,827 --> 01:37:17,977
Following her service at Abu Ghraib, Capt. Carolyn Wood was given a staff position

1148
01:37:17,977 --> 01:37:23,078
at the Army Interrogation School in Fort Huachuca, Arizona.

1149
01:37:23,078 --> 01:37:29,179
[Scott Horton, Attorney] What does that reflect in terms of Senior Leadership's intentions?

1150
01:37:29,179 --> 01:37:35,955
Not to eradicate the abuse, but to perpetuate the abuse.

1151
01:37:35,955 --> 01:37:40,990
I think the probabilities exist that there will be other terrorist attacks. That more Americans will die.

1152
01:37:40,990 --> 01:37:45,764
And the argument that we have to apply abuse to detainees in order to protect American lives,

1153
01:37:45,764 --> 01:37:52,050
I find to be violative of our deepest values And to the very safety of our country.

1154
01:37:52,050 --> 01:37:56,551
We fight not only to protect lives. We fight to protect our principles.

1155
01:37:56,941 --> 01:38:00,091
[Col. Lawrence Wilkerson, former Chief of Staff to Colin Powell] If you say, over the course of Afgan,

1156
01:38:00,091 --> 01:38:06,215
GTMO and Iraq, we've detained 50,000 people, I'd say that less than 1% were terrorists.

1157
01:38:13,136 --> 01:38:16,519
Were some of them insurgents? Probably.

1158
01:38:16,519 --> 01:38:22,303
Were almost all of them in Iraq, in particular, going to become insurgents after their treatment? Yes.

1159
01:38:22,303 --> 01:38:25,724
[Moazzam Begg, Detained at Bagram and Guantanamo] I was kidnapped, abducted, forced into prison,

1160
01:38:25,724 --> 01:38:31,563
tortured, and threatened with further torture, without charge. Without trial.

1161
01:38:33,063 --> 01:38:36,062
Even many soldiers had said to me afterward,

1162
01:38:36,062 --> 01:38:40,035
"Wasn't it hell when you weren't a terrorist when you came in here, by the time you leave,

1163
01:38:40,035 --> 01:38:43,071
I'm sure you would be because of the way you've been treated."

1164
01:38:45,637 --> 01:38:48,661
[Jack Cloonan, Counterterrorism Task Force] I think there's a certain level of prejudice

1165
01:38:48,661 --> 01:38:54,380
that this religion, and the people who have hijacked it,

1166
01:38:54,380 --> 01:38:59,686
have such a disregard for life, that we turn around and say,

1167
01:38:59,686 --> 01:39:10,270
"If they think so very little of life...and clearly 9/11 exemplified that...screw them!" Anything goes."

1168
01:40:02,620 --> 01:40:12,010
[Tim Golden, New York Times Reporter] It's not surprising that at the end of all this, Dilawar, the victim, was really lost.

1169
01:40:12,010 --> 01:40:17,559
I mean, Dilawar was almost invisible in the trials. I mean, you never saw pictures of him.

1170
01:40:17,559 --> 01:40:23,303
Nobody ever mentioned this man's wife and child who were left without a husband and father.

1171
01:40:23,581 --> 01:40:26,948
He was not part of the picture at all.

1172
01:40:42,159 --> 01:40:50,230
[Tim Golden, New York Times Reporter] There's a lot of other people out there who are going to run into this system unless it's fixed.

1173
01:40:50,230 --> 01:40:57,316
And you only need one to sort of remind yourself of what it's capable of.

1174
01:41:18,142 --> 01:41:24,335
[Alberto Mora, former Navy General Counsel] American values are premised upon the notion of human dignity, and the sanctity of the individual.

1175
01:41:24,335 --> 01:41:29,916
To allow for cruelty to be applied as a matter of official policy,

1176
01:41:29,916 --> 01:41:35,325
is to say that our forefathers were wrong about these inalienable rights.

1177
01:41:36,525 --> 01:41:42,231
[SPC. Tony Lagouranis, Mil-Intel, Iraq] Americans obviously want to believe that we're somehow more moral than the rest of the world.

1178
01:41:42,231 --> 01:41:45,279
For some reason we have a real strong desire to feel that way.

1179
01:41:45,279 --> 01:41:49,079
And I think that's eroding. I don't really know what effect that's going to have on us.

1180
01:41:49,079 --> 01:41:56,373
And I think a lot of people have just decided, "Well, you know, it's different now after 9/11.

1181
01:41:56,373 --> 01:42:01,169
We can't be good anymore. We have to get tough."

1182
01:42:01,169 --> 01:42:03,921
And so we'll have to see what that does to us.

1183
01:42:03,921 --> 01:42:05,111
What do you say?

1184
01:42:05,111 --> 01:42:07,821
[SPC. Tony Lagouranis, Mil-Intel, Iraq] I think that's bullshit, frankly.

1185
01:42:07,821 --> 01:42:13,949
I mean, I think that we still need to try and be as good as we can be.

1186
01:42:28,243 --> 01:42:32,449
[Frank B. Gibney] I find it utterly inconceivable that our highest officials...

1187
01:42:32,449 --> 01:42:40,596
Rumsfeld, Bush and Cheney...would not only countenance torture but would actually advocate it.

1188
01:42:40,596 --> 01:42:45,126
That really destroyed my faith in the American government.

1189
01:42:45,126 --> 01:42:50,532
Because through World War II and the Korean War, where I also served,

1190
01:42:50,532 --> 01:42:55,292
We had the sense that we were on the side of the good guys.

1191
01:42:55,292 --> 01:42:59,053
You'd always get justice from the United States of America.

1192
01:42:59,053 --> 01:43:03,778
People would get decent treatment. And there was a rule of law.

1193
01:43:03,778 --> 01:43:09,953
We never forgot that. That behind the facade of wartime hatreds,

1194
01:43:09,953 --> 01:43:15,125
There was a central rule of law which people abided by.

1195
01:43:16,048 --> 01:43:20,951
It was something we believed. It was what made America different.

